Project Structure & Standards
General Requirements
Follow latest web standards (ES modules, modern syntax, accessibility, semantic HTML where applicable).
Write clean, maintainable, and well-structured code.
Keep concerns separated and modular at all times.
Styling
All styles must be written in:
assets/css/styles.css
CSS must:
Be well-organized and clearly separated by sections

Use clear section comments, for example:

/* =========================
   Layout
========================= */

/* =========================
   Components - Calculator
========================= */
Follow modern best practices (CSS variables, responsive design, minimal duplication)
JavaScript Structure
All JavaScript must live inside:
assets/js/
Code organization rules:
Use a folder-per-concept structure
Each file should:
Have a single responsibility
Be small and focused
Prefer modular ES imports/exports
Example Structure
assets/js/
  calculator/
    service.js
    utils.js
    formatters.js
You may expand this structure as needed, but keep the same philosophy:
service.js → core logic
utils.js → reusable helpers
formatters.js → output/data formatting
Code Quality
All code must be:
Clearly commented, especially for non-obvious logic
Easy to read and reason about
Consistent in naming and structure
Use:
Descriptive function and variable names
JSDoc-style comments where helpful
Goal

Build a scalable, maintainable resource calculator that:

Can be easily extended with new resource chains
Keeps logic decoupled from UI
Is structured in a way that supports future growth

Act like a senior frontend engineer and prioritize clarity, maintainability, and scalability in every decision.